node.text:
ICYMI: A back-to-back #FireEcology bonanza with Dr. Gavin Jones giving us wildfire basics and Dr. Amy Christianson of the #GoodFirePodcast explaining cultural burns vs. prescribed fires and how Western science is starting to listen to thousands of years of Indigenous fire knowledge and strategy. As the West billows smoke and as both the #DixieFire and #CaldorFire rage on, it’s a great way to wrap our brains around the “WHY SUCH BIG FIRES, WHAT CAN WE DO?!” questions we have. 

(Video by @mindjammedia, Art by @bonidutch)

node.accessibility_caption: Amy Christianson stands in a golden grass field that is slowly burning. She is in a red flannel shirt and holding a drip torch, and a husky dog at her side looks into the distance. She is pregnant with her second daughter

node.text: Have you heard this week’s Indigenous Fire Ecology with Dr. Amy Christianson of the #GoodFirePodcast? If so, you’ll know my description didn’t do this photo justice 🔥❤️🔥

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Ologies on August 18, 2021 tagging @yourforestpodcast.

node.text: #IndigenousFireEcology (GOOD FIRE) with Dr. Amy Christianson is up! I promised you a follow-up to last week’s and the Doc delivered: hear all about her experiences with cultural burns, drip torches, wildfire strategies, spring burns, happy trees, elder evacuations and more. And listen to HER podcast, #GoodFire, with so many amazing Indigenous fire folks. Huge thanks to Matt Kristoff of @yourforestpodcast and Good Fire for lending us clips to supplement our recordings — follow them for more great foresty offerings. (Also weird sidenote: I haven’t posted about this episode for two days because there’s a giant fire raging near my parents’ house and I’ve been in a weird stupor refreshing fire websites to see if the house they JUST moved out of a few months ago will be rendered into ashes overnight. I hope everyone in line of the #CaldorFire gets to safety soon. Very thankful my folks moved closer to town.)

node.text: Have a BURNING curiosity about why everything’s on fire? This week, Dr. Gavin Jones aka @gavinskijones of the US Forest Service explains why we’re seeing more wildfire explosion — and gives a great primer for NEXT week’s Indigenous Fire Ecology episode. Also, arson, owls & ashes. 🔥 Link in bio, friends!

node.text: #FireEcology (WILDFIRES) with US Forest Service scientist Dr. Gavin Jones is up! Megafires, how plants have adapted, hospitable wombats, how fire has changed in the last century, mosaic ecosystems, prescribed burns, and hooting at owls for science. Also: tales of burning romance & arson. Have you ever had to evacuate for a fire? Make sure to read the motel reviews first.
